  "response": "George Lucas's reaction to *The Force Awakens* is a bit complicated and layered. Here's a summary of what's known:\n\n*   **Initial Disappointment:** Disney bought Lucasfilm and the Star Wars franchise in 2012. While Lucas provided some initial outlines and ideas for the sequel trilogy, his story treatments were ultimately not used. Lucas himself admitted to being disappointed that the filmmakers chose to go in a different direction. He famously said in an interview with Charlie Rose that he felt like he sold his kids to \"white slavers.\" While he quickly retracted this comment and apologized, it hinted at his feeling of disconnect from the new direction of the franchise.\n\n*   **A More Measured Tone Later:** After the initial sting, Lucas seemed to adopt a more positive and supportive stance. He publicly stated that he had seen the film and thought it was well-made. He also emphasized the importance of the franchise continuing with a new generation of storytellers.\n\n*   **Official Disney Stance:** Disney consistently maintained that Lucas was consulted and that they valued his input, even though they ultimately made their own decisions about the story.\n\n**In essence:**\n\n*   Lucas was initially disappointed because his ideas weren't used.\n*   He later took a more gracious approach, acknowledging the film's quality and the need for the franchise to evolve.\n*   His true feelings likely lie somewhere between those two extremes. He probably had mixed emotions, proud of the legacy he created but also feeling a sense of loss and detachment.\n\nIt's important to remember that Lucas had spent decades crafting the Star Wars universe, so it's understandable that he might have felt a strong connection to his own vision for the story.\n",
